<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
12/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 1
</SO>
<LP>
   GORBACHEV WON parliamentary support for sweeping new
executive powers.
   The Congress of People's Deputies voted to create a new
vice presidency and a cabinet under the Soviet leader's
direct control, marking a clear victory for the president and
for hard-liners. Also, Gorbachev quashed an effort by some
legislators to rein in his authority to issue decrees, and he
expressed anger at progressives trying to limit his
authority. On Monday, the Congress endorsed the concept of a
union treaty to hold the country together, and ordered the 15
republics to set dates for holding referendums on the
question.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Some of the Western humanitarian aid pouring into the
Soviet Union has been stolen, but more than 99% is reaching
the people who need it most, the KGB's chairman told the
legislators.
   ---
   Bush was advised by the top U.S. military commander in the
Gulf, Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf, that his ground forces won't
be fully prepared for an all-out assault against Iraq until
February, Pentagon officials said. Meanwhile, Iraqi
ambassadors headed home for urgent consultations with Saddam
Hussein.
   ---
   A Suriname army chief pledged following a bloodless coup
Monday that he would relinquish power to an elected
government within 100 days. Ivan Graanoogst, who joined with
other officers in overthrowing Suriname's President Ramsewak
Shankar, said he wouldn't impose a curfew because "there is
no danger whatsoever."
   ---
   A study by federal scientists failed to support a widely
circulated report that a gene related to alcoholism had been
discovered. In the new experiment, researchers said they
found that the putative alcoholism gene wasn't any more
common among 40 alcoholics than among 127 nonalcoholics.
   ---
   Salman Rushdie promised on Monday he won't authorize a
paperback version of his novel, "The Satanic Verses," and
said he doesn't agree with any statements made by characters
in the book that cast aspersions on Islam. Rushdie has been
in hiding in London since a February 1989 death edict by the
late Iranian leader Ayatollah Khomeini.
   ---
   The Israeli army upheld expulsion orders against four Gaza
Strip Palestinians but defense lawyers said they would submit
an appeal to Israel's Supreme Court. The army said a
three-officer appeals panel ruled that the Arabs were senior
leaders of an Islamic fundamentalist group involved in a
three-year-old Palestinian uprising.
                                                                                                       

   A Soviet envoy in Jerusalem presented his credentials as
consul-general to Israel, underscoring warming ties between
the Israelis and the Kremlin, which severed diplomatic
relations during the 1967 Middle East war. In a similar
ceremony in Moscow, an Israeli official presented his
credentials.
   ---
   A study found that teen suicide prevention programs in
schools may actually stir up depressed feelings rather than
help youths who have tried to kill themselves. The report is
published in today's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
   ---
   Serbia's ruling Communists won a landslide victory in
Yugoslavia's biggest republic, according to official results
from the first free Serbian elections since World War II,
held Sunday. The Communists, renamed Socialists, have lost
power this year in elections in four of Yugoslavia's six
republics.
   ---
   Romania's former monarch returned to his homeland after 43
years of exile, but faced the possibility of arrest. King
Michael, 69, who lives in Geneva, was forced by the
Communists to abdicate in 1947.
   ---
   San Francisco's mayor plans to sign a watered-down version
of a city ordinance requiring employers to provide health
safeguards for employees who use video display terminals. Art
Agnos met with business and union leaders last Saturday and
obtained general agreement to support six amendments limiting
the ordinance's scope.
   ---
   A Kashmiri Moslem group rejected an offer by Indian Prime
Minister Chandra Shekhar to negotiate with the rebels, who
want to secede from India. But in Punjab, where Sikhs also
are fighting for secession, a political leader said he was
prepared to talk to the government if he received a formal
invitation and a written agenda.
   ---
   Died: Karl H. Hinke, 84, a former executive vice president
of Marine Midland Bank and the creator of what is now known
as the MasterCard credit card, Saturday, in East Aurora, N.Y.
</TEXT>
