<HL>
   Enterprise -- State and Local Spotlight:
   State Legislators Take Closer Look at Managed Growth
   ---
   Small Firms Back Efforts to Prevent
   Backlash Against Development
   ----
   By Timothy D. Schellhardt
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 10
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)
CONSUMER &amp; HOUSEHOLD SERVICES, LAWN CARE, TAX PREPARATION (CSV)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   GROWTH MANAGEMENT elbows its way up the legislative agenda
in many states.
   Although budget and tax woes grab the biggest headlines,
two new surveys by the National Conference of State
Legislatures suggest that several issues of critical
importance to small business are emerging near the top of
many lawmakers' wish lists.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Among legislative leaders, interest grows significantly in
the issues of land use and how to manage growth. Leaders in
California, Florida, Hawaii, Maryland, Oregon, Rhode Island
and Washington identified both among their top priorities for
1991. Leaders in Arizona, California, Delaware, Maryland and
Pennsylvania say growth management is particularly important
for the longer-term interests of their states.
   The issues "have been a fairly low profile kind of topic
before," notes Doug Sacarto, the NCSL's state-issues
director. But lawmakers say that failure to address them
"will lead to a backlash to stifle economic development," he
says.
   In a separate survey, states' legislative-committee
chairmen continue to rank a half dozen small-business topics
very high for deliberation in 1991. For spurring economic
development, efforts to expand tourism and foreign trade
rated highest, followed by aid to distressed communities,
especially rural areas. Lawmakers in 29 states listed
assistance to start-up enterprises as important, and those in
27 states cited efforts to develop high-technology
businesses.
   Next year's agenda on labor issues apparently again will
focus on corralling workers' compensation costs; 40 states
ranked that as their top labor issue. Other issues moving up:
family-leave policies for employees, job retraining and
employee drug testing. The small-business lobby favors a
workers' compensation overhaul and generally opposes
mandatory family-leave measures.
   But interest wanes in helping troubled and mature
industries. Only nine states gave a priority label to issues
such as plant-closing legislation and state financing to help
turn around failing companies.
   ---
   NEW ENGLAND, Mid-Atlantic states register big gains in
black-owned firms.
   Nationally, the number of black-owned firms rose 38%
between 1982 and 1987, to 424,165 from 308,260, a new Census
Bureau report shows. Posting the strongest growth were
several New England and East Coast states, while Pacific
states showed the slowest growth.
   New Hampshire led the nation with an 86% gain, spurred by
a proliferation of service-related businesses, though the
number of black-owned businesses there remains low at just
229. Wyoming, bringing up the rear, actually had a 10% drop
in such businesses, to 81 from 90.
   Regionally, New England had a 68% increase in the
five-year period, followed by the Mid-Atlantic states of New
Jersey, New York and Pennsylvania, with a 50% increase, and
the eight-state South Atlantic region, at 47%. The slowest
growth came in the Pacific states, with a 23% increase; the
Great Lakes states, at 27%; and the South-Central states, at
28%.
   California has the most black-owned businesses, 47,728,
followed by New York, 36,289, and Texas, 35,725. States with
fewer than 100 black-owned firms: North Dakota (the only
state without a black-owned manufacturing firm), South
Dakota, Montana, Wyoming and Vermont, the survey said.
   ---
     Where Black-Owned Firms' Growth Is Fastest, Slowest
                                                                                                       

