   ---
   ONE-STOP SHOPPING: Toledo, Ohio, officials have
established a Central Permit Center downtown that speedily
issues any of the city's 112 different permits. Previously,
people starting a business and other applicants had to go to
each department involved. Officials think the center may be
bringing in more permit fees because its convenience keeps
prospective applicants from giving up in frustration.
   ---
   CLEANING UP: Arizona, South Carolina and Tennessee have
eased procedures allowing laundromats and dry cleaners to
dispose of unclaimed items. New Jersey moves to make it
easier for these firms to get rid of unclaimed carpets. And
Connecticut lawmakers reduce to one from two the number of
required inspections of dry cleaners by fire marshals,
reports State Net, which tracks legislation.
   ---
   WARY WATCHDOGS: For three years, members of the Council of
Independent Business Owners in Asheville, N.C., have been
monitoring city and Buncombe County governing boards. The
upshot: The small-business group this month filed a petition
for a 10% cut in Asheville property taxes and asked that the
city council or Asheville residents vote on the plan early
next year. The business owners said their monitoring
convinced them "the only way to achieve a more frugal
government is through a forced reduction in funding."
   ---
   STATES SEEK increasingly to link small business to
anti-illiteracy efforts.
   A tax credit for Mississippi businesses went into effect
early this year and Colorado lawmakers are expected to
consider a similar measure to be introduced next month.
Businesses can write off 25% of any direct costs for
providing basic-skills training to employees.
   Colorado's comprehensive literacy bill is expected to
include several other provisions to tap small-business help,
including grants for workplace literacy training. Jim
Henderson, a regional small-business advocate at the Small
Business Administration, says chances "are good" that some
form of literacy legislation will pass.
   Mr. Henderson notes that about half the state's lawmakers
attended at least one of 15 literacy hearings around the
state this fall. A 1985 study placed the illiteracy rate for
Colorado adults at 8%, lower than the 13% national average,
but Mr. Henderson thinks it's actually higher.
   In South Carolina, with a 15% adult illiteracy rate, the
governor's office has held talks with business owners to
promote literacy efforts.
</TEXT>
