<HL>
   And if This Doesn't Do the Trick,
   They May Call for Squirrel Rifles
   ----
   By Ann Hagedorn
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 9
</SO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<LP>
   Balloons make good targets.
   Environmentalists have long said balloons that land in the
sea choke marine life. Now California says metallic balloons
do a number on power lines.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   So, starting Jan. 1, Californians who unleash
helium-filled metallic balloons will be committing a crime
under a new law. First-time offenders will be fined $100, and
repeat offenders face as long as six months in jail and a
$1,000 fine.
   The new balloon law results from the lobbying efforts of
California utilities and the state's Public Utilities
Commission. Their crusade was inspired by a commission report
that fugitive metallic balloons and their streamers cause
nearly 1% of California's power outages each year.
   Metallic balloons, on the market since the early 1970s,
are made of aluminum-coated nylon. They stay aloft longer
than latex balloons because the aluminum coating prevents the
helium, which has very tiny atoms, from leaking out. Metallic
balloons account for about $400 million of the nation's $1
billion balloon industry.
   Utility companies were so concerned about the commission's
findings that they wanted to ban the sale of the balloons.
But the Silver Balloon Association, a Sacramento-based group
representing metallic-balloon vendors and manufacturers,
convinced legislators that such a ban would devastate
thousands of small businesses.
   "Squirrels and birds cause nearly 2.5% of the outages,"
says Silver Balloon Director Lisa Rea. "And automobiles and
the weather cause a lot more. But you can't ban squirrels,
birds and storms; so they went after balloons."
   As of Jan. 1, the sale or distribution of any balloon
attached to metallic ribbons or streamers will be prohibited.
Metallic balloons must have a weight attached and bear a
label warning consumers about the dangers that balloons pose
for power lines. And vendors can sell metallic balloons in
bunches only if the balloons are attached to an object, like
a mug or a key chain.
   Still, balloon companies don't seem too deflated.
   Alan Harris, a vice president of M&amp;D Balloons, a large
U.S. balloon maker, thinks the weighted balloons will be
popular. "The new product will prevent a child from losing a
balloon in a grocery store with 20-foot ceilings. And there
will no longer be a need for people to tie their balloons to
their desks or weight them down with a book, only to lose the
balloon once the book is lifted . . . We're optimistic."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901226-0061
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901226-0061.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Monday's Markets:
   Industrials
   Drop 12.37,
   Bonds Ease
   ---
   Foreign Exchange Is
   Bright Spot as Dollar
   Gains on Mark, Yen
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 13
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
U.S. STOCK MARKET STATISTICS (STT)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Grinches raided the financial markets Christmas Eve.
   While many traders and investors found ample reason Monday
not to be in their offices, the diehards who showed up were
decidedly pessimistic. The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost
12.37 points to close at 2621.29 in a short pre-holiday
trading session. Bond traders bid the prices of long-term
Treasury bonds down. The only bright spot was in the foreign
exchange market, where the dollar posted gains against both
the mark and the yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Traders said weekend saber rattling spooked investors
Monday. Secretary of Defense Richard Cheney said Saturday
that "the clock is ticking" quickly toward a war in the
Middle East. Iraq's President Saddam Hussein, meanwhile, said
Tel Aviv will be Iraq's first target if war breaks out. And
in Israel, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said the danger of
war "is very close." Adding to concerns was Iraq's recall of
its ambassadors to the U.S. and United Nations for talks in
Iraq.
   In the bond market, the war worries combined with year-end
profit-taking to drive prices of long-term Treasury bonds
down sharply. The more popular short-term debt securities
were off only modestly, even though the bond market is
bracing for the sale later this week of a record $12.5
billion of two-year Treasury notes and a record $8.5 billion
of four-year notes. Thin trading volume exacerbated the
downward trend, analysts said.
   Trading on the New York Stock Exchange was thin, too.
Volume on the Big Board totaled a mere 57.2 million shares,
eclipsing the previous slowest day of the year when 63.4
million shares traded on the day after Thanksgiving. The
stock exchange closed at 2 p.m. Monday, two hours earlier
than usual.
   Laszlo Birinyi, a market analyst with his own research
firm, said that despite the down day on Christmas Eve, the
stock market hasn't performed badly in recent weeks.
"Everyone is sitting around pooh-poohing this as a bear
market rally, but it is a 10% rally" from the October lows.
What's more, he said, so far this year the market is down a
mere 1% on a total return basis, which takes into account
dividends as well as price changes. "It hasn't been all that
bad a year," he said.
   "Overall, we're seeing some positive things," he said.
"The people on Wall Street are very negative, but if you look
at how well many investors did in 1990, all the negative news
gets confusing."
   Even all the concern about the Middle East doesn't seem to
have a very damping effect on stocks, he said. "The Middle
East is obviously a question mark, but if you look at the
prices of crude oil and gold as a proxy for investor concern
about the Middle East, you would have to think the market is
relatively unconcerned." Gold prices are almost unchanged
since the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in August and, while the
price of oil shot up as high as $40 a barrel, it has since
fallen to about $27, up from a 12-month low of about $15.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices fell. Declining issues on the Big Board
outpaced gainers, 842 to 527.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices were down sharply. The Treasury's benchmark
30-year bond lost seven-eighths of a point, or about $8.75
for each $1,000 of face amount. The yield on the issue rose
to 8.36%.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar gained. In New York trading the currency was
quoted at 1.5440 marks and 136.00 yen, compared with 1.5289
marks and 135.55 yen Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901226-0060
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901226-0060.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Older Rebel Does Own Thing
   ----
   By Andrew Blum
</HL>
<DATE>
12/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 5
</SO>
<LP>
   New York -- When Richie Havens sang "Freedom" at Woodstock
in 1969, little did he know that 21 years later it would
still be his biggest hit. But his Woodstock-earned reputation
has allowed him to parlay singing into his own sort of
freedom: the chance to do what he wants.
   Sitting in his company's midtown Manhattan office
recently, Havens, an imposing but friendly figure with hands
full of rings, expounded on music, a new album due out next
month, television and radio ads, environmental projects and
philosophy, always philosophy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   On the subject of Woodstock, Havens said he wishes the
event was more understood. "Kids are discovering Woodstock
every day . . . It's been a 20-year job for me just defending
Woodstock's actuality." Folklore has it that Woodstock was
his big break, but Havens stressed that he had performed
overseas by 1969 and had done albums by then. Nevertheless,
the legendary outdoor concert certainly didn't hurt his
popularity, and he was the first performer on stage, thanks
to a twist of fate. "I went on first because there was no one
else there to go on," he said. All the other groups were
still stuck in traffic.
   Havens is a man who insists he's happy scrambling. At 49,
he claims fans of all ages and appears at jazz, rock, folk
and blues concerts. But he hasn't always enjoyed big
financial success with his records. "So many companies," he
said; "the minute I put out an album they go out of
business." But, he added, "I don't need a record to allow me
to work."
   A guitarist/singer who performs with backup guitar or
four-piece band, Havens has done 19 albums, three of them
gold (sales of more than 500,000). He has also done
soundtracks for the television program "The Wonder Years" and
the film "Coming Home." One of his latest albums, "Simple
Things" (RBI), sold more than 100,000 copies in the U.S.
after it was issued two years ago, but then RBI folded. He
reissued the record in Europe recently on his own ELO label
and it sold 40,000 copies in Italy alone.
   These are not astounding figures. Indeed, Havens's career
has been a tepid affair since the '60s, perhaps because of
the kind of music he performs. "Richie Havens is essentially
an interpretive singer in the folk genre," said Rolling
Stone's Anthony DeCurtis, the point being that interpretive
singers in the folk genre didn't ship much platinum in the
'70s and '80s. But Havens stayed alive and his number may be
coming up again, in the wake of recent successes by folky
artists such as Tracy Chapman. Mr. DeCurtis thinks it's "not
impossible for Richie Havens to stage a comeback."
   Johanan Vigoda, the Los Angeles co-producer of Havens's
upcoming album, called "Richie Havens Now," has his sights
set high for a commercial success. The album, which will
include a Jimi Hendrix song, one Cyndi Lauper tune and eight
to 10 originals, will be released by Solar Records, a soul
label distributed by CBS. That, Mr. DeCurtis remarked, should
be a boost to Havens, who has suffered in the past under
smaller labels that lacked marketing and promotion clout. "A
lot of people have heard of him, but have never heard him,"
said Mr. Vigoda, a long-time industry hand who represents
Stevie Wonder.
   Actually, millions have heard Havens without knowing it.
He sings jingles for a variety of commercials. The Woodstock
rebel's voice now hymns Amtrak, Folgers coffee, Bell
Atlantic, MasterCard, Kodak and others. He won a 1990 Clio
award for an ad he sung for the cotton industry.
   "I like Richie Havens," said Amtrak spokesman Clifford
Black. "Havens's voice gives {the ad} a signature that makes
it special."
   The jingle business can bring a volume singer in New York
as much as $10,000 under union scale in residuals over the
life of a commercial. Havens earns over scale, industry
executives say. And, added Mr. DeCurtis, Havens's jingles are
"very lucrative," noting "no one's going to have to take up a
collection for Richie Havens." Havens himself downplays the
part played by jingles in his current career: "Every jingle
house calls me up and I refuse most. It's not my business.
The ads are projects. I support my own ideas in that kind of
way."
   Havens does indeed seem to be constantly in motion, doing
concerts "all over the planet" every weekend in large and
small settings. His recent schedule included a trip to Prague
for two days for an Italian television special with Joe
Cocker and Billy Preston, then California a few days later.
He also performed at a concert honoring Nelson Mandela in New
York earlier this year.
   Time was, of course, he was on the road every day, but he
says he has cut his traveling to three or four days a week,
to leave time for a variety of projects. The North Wind
Underseas Institute on New York's City Island, which he
co-founded, developed a device to rescue whales and teaches
harbor seals to rescue people trapped underwater. He is also
starting a cable project called Weekend Future Television.
   If the new album takes off, the only thing Havens will
have to worry about is another jingle singer who imitates the
Havens voice so well that "a lot of times I thought it was
me, too."
   ---
   Mr. Blum is a reporter for the National Law Journal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
