   Business Brief -- U.S. Home Corp.:
   Some Debt Retired, Accord
   Is Set on Paying Off More
</HL>
<DATE>
12/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 19
</SO>
<CO>
   UH
</CO>
<IN>
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   U.S. Home Corp. said that during the fourth quarter, it
retired $10 million principal amount of subordinated debt and
agreed to retire an additional $11.5 million of subordinated
debt and $7.5 million of senior debt.
   The Houston-based home builder said the agreement involves
two institutional holders and provides for exchanging the
debt for certain real property and mortgage notes not being
used in the current business operations. Completion of the
transactions will result in annual interest savings of more
than $3.9 million, the company said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company also said that, in connection with continuing
discussions with its banks on restructuring its $156 million
credit agreement, the banks have agreed to reschedule to Feb.
1 a $5 million amortization payment that was due Dec. 17.
